04949nam a22006375i 9780674020634DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20092006mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740206347 a10.4159/97806740206342doi  a(DE-B1597)584829  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aHD4965.2b.B43 2004eb 7aBUS0100002bisacsh04a331.2/8165842221 aBebchuk, Lucian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPay without Performance :bThe Unfulfilled Promise of Executive Compensation /cLucian Bebchuk, Jesse Fried. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2009] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tPart I The Official View and Its Shortcomings -- t1 The Official Story -- t2 Have Boards Been Bargaining at Arm’s Length? -- t3 Shareholders’ Limited Power to Intervene -- t4 The Limits of Market Forces -- tPart II Power and Pay -- t5 The Managerial Power Perspective -- t6 The Relationship between Power and Pay -- t7 Managerial Influence on the Way Out -- t8 Retirement Benefits -- t9 Executive Loans -- tPart III Decoupling Pay from Performance -- t10 Non-Equity-Based Compensation -- t11 Windfalls in Conventional Options -- t12 Excuses for Conventional Options -- t13 More on Windfalls in Equity-Based Compensation -- t14 Freedom to Unwind Equity Incentives -- tPart IV Going Forward -- t15 Improving Executive Compensation -- t16 Improving Corporate Governance -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe company is under-performing, its share price is trailing, and the CEO gets.a multi-million-dollar raise. This story is familiar, for good reason: as this book clearly demonstrates, structural flaws in corporate governance have produced widespread distortions in executive pay. Pay without Performance presents a disconcerting portrait of managers' influence over their own pay--and of a governance system that must fundamentally change if firms are to be managed in the interest of shareholders.Lucian Bebchuk and Jesse Fried demonstrate that corporate boards have persistently failed to negotiate at arm's length with the executives they are meant to oversee. They give a richly detailed account of how pay practices--from option plans to retirement benefits--have decoupled compensation from performance and have camouflaged both the amount and performance-insensitivity of pay. Executives' unwonted influence over their compensation has hurt shareholders by increasing pay levels and, even more importantly, by leading to practices that dilute and distort managers' incentives.This book identifies basic problems with our current reliance on boards as guardians of shareholder interests. And the solution, the authors argue, is not merely to make these boards more independent of executives as recent reforms attempt to do. Rather, boards should also be made more dependent on shareholders by eliminating the arrangements that entrench directors and insulate them from their shareholders. A powerful critique of executive compensation and corporate governance, Pay without Performance points the way to restoring corporate integrity and improving corporate performance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCorporate governance. 0aExecutivesxSalaries, etc. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Business Law.2bisacsh1 aFried, Jesse, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z978311044221240uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674020634?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674020634423Coveruhttps://ww